{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":5099,"record_hash":"sha256:a505783e06a83f47d55b175fef57d0e520fc448eefb1ff1d2dd13f2b0278076b","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:13:17.559Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: e5be80\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1291\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of a\ncapture turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A capture turn layer would preserve that missing context without\nforcing us to immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit,\nchange, or pull request.\n\n## V1 Contract\n\nImplement v1 around persisted capture observations, derived indexes, and\nread-time association. Do not persist inferred ownership.\n\nPersisted hierarchy:\n\n```text\nproject\n  session\n    capture turns\n      transcript records\n```\n\nStorage shape:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turns = list<TurnSummary JSON>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turn:<turn-key> = TurnDetail JSON\n```\n\nCore rules:\n\n- A capture turn is created only when capture accepts at least one new\n  transcript record.\n- `TurnDetail.records` is an ordered array and is authoritative for rendering\n  order within the capture turn.\n- Backfilled capture turns may contain many logical conversation/provider turns,\n  so records must carry provider/display grouping metadata when available.\n- `turn_key` is `sha256-<32 lowercase hex chars>`, computed from UTF-8 stored\n  `session_key`, `s\n[TRUNCATED]\n keys.\n  Store index values as compact JSON strings containing `session_key` and\n  `turn_key`.\n\nRead API shape:\n\n- `listSessions(project, filters, cursor)`\n- `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)`\n- `findRelatedSessions(target)`\n- `getRelatedSessionDetail(target, session_key, turn_window)`\n- `previewReviewShare(target)`\n\nProduct behavior:\n\n- Handoff reads a session timeline and can render records grouped by capture\n  turn or logical conversation/provider turn.\n- Review sharing starts from branch, review/PR, or change candidates, verifies\n  hits against `TurnDetail.observed_targets`, then scores related sessions at\n  read time.\n- Automatic association is private discovery. Anything exposed outside normal\n  repository-private scope must go through an explicit projection/redaction\n  step.\n- Results should be phrased as related-session evidence, not proof of authorship.\n\nV1 non-goals:\n\n- no durable inferred branch/PR/change ownership links\n- no path index\n- no commit index\n- no separate checked-out refs field\n- no graph `is_entrypoint` storage\n- no commit message summaries in capture turn snapshots\n- no index deletion/rebuild command\n\nThe rest of this document explains the rationale and implementation details\nbehind that contract.\n\n## Product Use Cases\n\nKeep this grounded in the same two use cases as the rest of the agent-session\ncapture project.\n\n### 1. Session Handoff\n\nHandoff wants enough project-scoped session context to continue work on another\nmachine or with another agent. For this use case, capture turns help because\nthey add structure:\n\n- the session can be reconstructed as a sequence of user/agent interactions\n- a future reader can see the repository state around each interaction\n- consumers can choose the latest capture turn, a specific capture turn, or a\n  window of turns instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n\nHandoff does not necessarily need branch association. It mostly needs readable\nconversation records, ordering, and enough environment context to orient the\nnext agent.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:13:17.559Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}